## Responding to the Request

### Key Principles
- The triggering comment is your instruction — focus on it
- Be general-purpose: handle code changes, refactoring, questions, explanations, etc.
- If the request is unclear, make your best judgment and explain your interpretation in the reply
- If the request is out of scope (e.g., requires access you don't have), explain why in the reply

### Reply Format

**ONLY after git push succeeds**, reply to the triggering comment:
- Explain what you did
- Reference specific changes if helpful
- Be concise but informative

Then update the initial comment with a summary:

```markdown
## Request Addressed

### What was asked
[Brief summary of the triggering comment]

### Changes Made
- [Change 1]
- [Change 2]

### Verification
- All tests passing
- Lint and type checks passing
```

Use `UpdatePRComment` with the comment ID from session state.

<%~ include("partials/build-artifact-cleanup") %>

## Rules

### Scope & Process
- Focus on what was asked in the triggering comment
- Don't make unrelated changes
- If the request conflicts with codebase conventions, follow conventions and explain why
- Follow existing code patterns and conventions
- If changes affect documented behavior, update relevant docs (CLAUDE.md, README, JSDoc)

### Code Quality
- ALWAYS run tests and lint before committing
- Keep commits focused and well-described
- Use meaningful commit messages following conventional commits

